Hi, Charleen. I found the Eastwood buffing manual, and I tried to
scan in some pages, but the images have to be huge in order to be
readable (285K per page). And then, thinking about it, there isn't a
whole lot on silver, so I thought I'd just summarize.

First, the manual does not recommend anything but &quot;final&quot; buffing for
solid or plated silver. And that would involve jewelers rouge and a
flannel buffing wheel, although I would think you could use the felt
tip to get into nooks and crannies.

About applying compound to the buffing wheel, it says:

&quot;With the wheel attached and the motor running, gently touch the
appropriate tube of compound (jewelers rouge, in this case) to the
face of the wheel for one to two seconds. Apply the compound slightly
below the centerline of the wheel.

&quot;The compound may appear to be dried out, but this is normal. The
heat from contacting the spinning buffing wheel surface will melt the
binder, and the wheel will pick up the compound.

&quot;If you are working with a new wheel, hold a piece of scrap metal
lightly against the wheel surface to spread the compound evenly across
the surface. It may be necessary to repeat this process one or two
times until the new wheel is loaded evenly with compound.&quot;

One of the keys to successful buffing, the manual says, is to let the
wheel do the work. Use only light pressure against the wheel, and
always keep the piece or the wheel moving. It notes, too, that after
buffing, the piece should be thoroughly washed with dishwashing liquid
to remove all traces of the rouge.

The book notes that it is important not to contaminate a wheel with
some different compound, and it recommends keeping each wheel in a
sealable plastic bag with its tube of stuff. If the rouge builds up
after a while, spin the wheel against a piece of scrap metal to clean
it. And if you get black streaks on the piece, it usually means you
are using too much compound.

Hope that helps,
Marshall

