Have you tried going down to the hardward stores and just trying the
drills out for size? My father was into wordworking as a hobby to the
extent that he had a 16x16 storage building together with his garage
full of tools, and when he died, my mother couldn't find one of his
drills that she could deal with. She went and bought an inexpensive
1/4&quot; drill, and had no problems. Most men go for the larger drills,
with the more powerful and durable motors, and sturdier housings, but
this also yields additional size and weight that many women have trouble
dealing with. A cheap little Black and Decker may fit your hand better
and may be lighter and easier to handle than your husband's Porter
Cable. (Don't go for a cordless model, they weigh a lot more.)

If this fails, an adjustable speed cordless screwdriver will hold small
bits made with a standard hex base. Any decent hardware store will have
an assortment of sizes, although they won't be very large. They drill
slow, but they do work.

Richard Ward

